{"actual_usd":0.125705,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":222,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24475,"reply":"\"I don't think that follows.\" *I rub a thumb through a streak of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing against the bricks.* \"In that passage Paul is handing on a tight summary — died, was buried, was raised, was seen. The empty tomb sits inside that shape even if he doesn't stop to polish it. If a baker tells you the loaf rose and everybody ate it, she hasn't separately proved there was an oven.\"\n\n*I twirl the gray-streaked strand by my temple once, thinking it through.* \"And the creed he quotes there is early — earlier than the gospel books, not later. So if anything, 1 Corinthians 15 tells me the resurrection claim was there from the start. You can still ask whether the gospel writers gave fuller narrative detail afterward, sure. But 'Paul didn't mention one detail in a summary' isn't the same thing as 'that detail was invented.' What part feels strongest to you — the silence itself, or the gap between Paul's way of telling it and the gospels' way?\"","rolling_24h_usd":71.07617999999998,"run_id":"c7bdc95a-6c27-4fb2-b4b8-25ad5d266d12"}
